postcontent:
I am selling 3 rifles in my collection in order to make some room in my safe. I am open to trades as well, so let me know what you've got!

Mosin Nagant carbine - receiver is dated 1953 w matching bolt, receiver, barrel, and magazine well.  Soviet hammer and sickle clearly visible on receiver above serial number, bolt is smooth as butter, and barrel has strong grooves.  asking $200

German K98 - this is an original Nazi Germany pre-war Mauser.  receiver is stamped S27 and dated 1937 making this a pre-war product of the famed Erfurter Maschinenfabrik (ERMA) factory.  side of receiver is stamped w the gothic Mod.98, as well as the German Eagles.  bolt has Nazi Eagle complete w swastika stamped behind bolt to indicate test fire proof.  this is an all numbers matching rifle w the exception of the forward barrel band.  rifle was not made w a front side hood as was customary for pre-war rifles.  she is a fantastic shooter and an irreplaceable piece of history, as this rifle most definitely saw action in the Second World War. asking $1700

M1 Garand - this is a CMP rifle w Springfield Armory receiver, trigger group, barrel, and gas block.  serial number indicates this is a July 1944 manufacture.  there is a rack number "23" written on the hand hold of the stock, and I have a beautiful leather repro sling on her.  she has eaten every 30-06 round I have fed her without a single jam, FTF, or stove pipe.  great shooter and a great piece of American military history.  I have a ton of enblocs and B andoleers I can include as well.  asking $800

I am open to trades don't forget, so let me know what you have to offer!  I am in search of a Springfield 1903 and an American Enfield.

The original H&R firm was in business for over a century from 1871 to 1986.
Frank Wesson started a firearms manufacturing firm in 1859, sharing an early patent with Nathan Harrington. He started a brief partnership in 1871 with his nephew Gilbert Henderson Harrington, as Wesson & Harrington, until Harrington bought him out in 1874.

In 1875 Harrington and another former Wesson employee, William Augustus Richardson, formed the new Harrington & Richardson Company. In 1888 the firm was incorporated as The Harrington & Richardson Arms Company. 

In the 1960s H&R was acquired by the Kidde corporation and run by the Rowe family in Gardner, Massachusetts. The original H&R company went out of business in 1986. A new company, H&R 1871, Inc., was formed in 1991 and started production of revolvers, single-shot rifles and shotguns using original H&R designs. H&R 1871, Inc. assets were subsequently sold to H&R 1871, LLC., a Connecticut LLC owned by Marlin Firearms Company in November 2000. Marlin, including all its H&R assets, was later acquired by Remington Arms Company in December, 2007

postcontent:
WALTHER PP 32ACP, High Polish, 2 Magazines, Made in GERMANY, Like New in Presentation Case, also includes a rare German PP manual. Some facts about the 
different Walther's:
Walther PP vs. PPK vs. PPK/S There are several variants of the Walther PP, the basic story is that the PP has a longer slide and barrel, and a metal backstrap. The PPK is shorter than the PP by 0.6″ and has no metal backstrap, so the grips wrap around the rear. The PPK also has a shorter grip, and the magazines hold one less round. The PPK/S is a combination of the two. It has the shorter barrel and slide of the PPK, but the longer grip of the PP. The original chambering was .32 ACP (or 7.62mm in Europe) but all three variants have also been offered in .380 ACP, .25 ACP and .22 LR.

Dr. No is the first entry in the official James Bond film series and marked the debut of Sean Connery as Agent 007. The 1962 film follows Bond as he investigates the murder of a British agent that leads him to a diabolical scientist who has taken over an entire island for his criminal enterprises. While Bond's signature PPK is mentioned in the film, the actual pistol carried is a Walther PP.

title: For Sale:  SIG (Hammerli) P240, .32 S&W-Lwc

postcontent:
Guns are on hold pending confirmation of sale.Shipping available.  Two Hammerli SIG P240 available.  ONE and only one in .32 (images 1,2) and ONE COMPLETE 3 caliber set.Armslist sometimes does not forward inquiries.  If that happens, please see my Hammerli 208 listing (text) or GSP listing (images) for other contact routes.The grip on this gun does NOT have an adjustable shelf.  It is the best and most perfectly cut grip I've ever encountered for a medium to large size hand.  This gun (.32 only) is in the SECOND and THIRD images.  The first is the 3-caliber set.  The ideal firearms for security and protective work, where collateral damage (death of bystanders, property damage) are to be kept to zero or close to that. Not quite the old KGB favorite for that purpose, but nearly as accurate and more reliable in function.  Email for more images.  Many of the other guns are under Listings by this User which also is http://www.armslist.com/classifieds/search?relatedto=4574568   Several grips are available, including a LH grip for this gun (Hammerli OEM).  FINAL PRICE depends on which grip you choose.  The listed price is for the P240 in .32 only AS SHOWN.  Price is higher with other grips, or for the complete set, which is $5200 as shown.  The P240 in .38 was the prototype of nearly all the SigArms and SIG Sauer guns that followed. In either caliber, it is quite different from the P210, although there are similarities.  In .32 (the caliber advertised), the gun uses an inertial breech lock, not the dropping barrel lock of the .38 or the SigSauer guns. The frame uses a sloped grip, like the GSP, and not a right angle grip. Trigger is single stage and fixed position, but is adjustable for pull weight and lash.  This gun is one of the best of the .32 available. Not as accurate as the TriAce due to barrel design, it and the GSP are "second best" by comparison, but that is a very high comparison mark.  Price is with one magazine. Unfortunately due to slow processing at ATF, others would be obtainable from the commercial market at this time.  Also available are  Steyr Match pistol .22lr (R or LH grip) Full nickel factory plated Walther GSP in .22lr/32,  Hammerli Sig P240 in ALL 3 CALIBER SET (.38, .32, .22lr)--$5200Hammerli 208 S commemorative model $2500 Hammerli 208 with factory safety, 2 magazines $1500 Walther GSP, Walther OSP (all versions, 10" barrel) $800 to 3600 Hi Standard Victors (Hamden 5.5" barrels only) $770 up Whitney marked WOLVERINE, & one typical, not wolverine-marked $1200 M96 Swedish Mauser in 6.5x55 with Elit diopter sights, target trigger, and pistol grip, 400 rd Norma sniper/match ammo  Discounts can be applied on request to multiple gun purchases, usually 10% of the higher priced gun or guns, with a few exceptions.  Transfer can be on an IL FOID card after state police approval, or to NH residents with any of the several forms of ID acceptable there. Shipping to FFL holder for transfer also is available. Cost depends on shipping rates, and if receiving FFL holder accepts incoming guns from individuals.   NOT a commercial dealer.  No credit cards, PayPal, and no special orders or requests for guns I do not currently have in my collection.
If you want this gun for pickup in NH, let me know by mid-May.
To avoid confusion, these guns were NOT made by SigSauer. They WERE made by SIG in a sense, when they owned Hammerli. The Caliber is .32S&W-WC. The gun will not fire the standard .32 S&W or .32 ACP cartridges, although some have modified them for .32 ACP. In addition to being superb target guns, some really like them for defense and security work, due to the extreme accuracy and lack of misfeed, and ability to minimize unintended injury. This caliber was a KGB favorite for that use, although the SAKO TriAce was the preferred gun in that caliber. Due to the bullet configuration and low noise, they can be used in "home based" target ranges due to the limited backstop required, compared to 9x19 cartridges. Accuracy is much better than the best 9x19 or .45ACP Target gun to about 35 yards. Beyond that, accuracy drops off with this gun, unless slight barrel modification is used.
